METHODOLOGY:
This bill amends RSA 126-Z, the Right to Try Act, by requiring any health care provider
providing any type of care under RSA 126-Z to report specific information, in writing, to the
facility in which the care is rendered. Facilities would be responsible for reporting data to the
Department of Health and Human Services, which would be required to make an annual
aggregated report to the General Court. The Department would be required to adopt rules
relative to (1) the form in which the data shall be filed; (2) the cadence of reporting from
facilities; (3) the confidentiality of data collected and disclosed; and (4) procedures and written
requirements for obtaining, using, and protecting data provided by the Department. The bill
allows for the imposition of a $100 per day administrative fine upon any medical facility that
willfullyfailstocomplywithitsprovisions.
TheDepartmentnotesthatChapter287,Lawsof2025requiresittoestablishareportingsystem
to collect reporting related to abortion statistics. Although that law has a later effective date
(January 1, 2027) than the bill contemplated here (60 days after passage), the Department could
potentially leverage that system to satisfy both requirements. If so, the Department estimates a
one-time cost of $97,000 to create a reporting module for the Right to Try Act, and ongoing
annual maintenance and personnel costs of $105,000 in FY28 and $130,000 in FY29 to establish

a developer/programmer position to provide technical support both to the internal program(s)
andexternalITstaffinfacilities.
The Department states that in the event it is unable to leverage the reporting system required
by the 2025 law, it would need 8-10 months to develop and establish a surveillance reporting
system utilizing. The Department would need to establish a Memorandum of Understanding
(MOU) with the Office Professional Licensure and Certification (OPLC) to connect to OPLC’s
licensing database for validating the health care facility. The Department estimates the cost at
$882,000 in SFY 27, along with personnel costs of $121,000 in FY28 and $149,000 in FY29 to
establishonefull-timesystemadministrator.
Depending on the options available, therefore, the bill's cost could range from $97,000 to
$882,000 in FY27, $105,000 to $121,000 in FY28, and $130,000 to $149,000 in FY29. It is
assumedthattheseexpenseswouldbeallgeneralfunds.
